---

<DocsLayout title="Workspace - ThinkPad - Docs" sidebar={sidebar} toc={toc} issuesUrl="https://github.com/ether-strannik/PrismChart/issues">
	<style>
		h1 {
			font-size: 1.8rem;
			font-weight: 600;
			margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
		}

		.tagline {
			color: #666;
			margin-bottom: 2rem;
		}

		h2 {
			font-size: 1.2rem;
			font-weight: 600;
			margin: 2rem 0 1rem;
			padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
			border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e5e5;
		}

		h2:first-of-type {
			margin-top: 0;
		}

		p {
			color: #333;
			margin-bottom: 1rem;
		}

		.section-intro {
			font-weight: 500;
			color: #000;
			margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
		}

		img {
			max-width: 100%;
			border-radius: 6px;
			margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
		}

		.note {
			color: #666;
			font-size: 0.95rem;
			padding: 1rem;
			background: #f5f5f5;
			border-radius: 4px;
			margin: 1.5rem 0;
		}
	</style>

	<h1>Workspace</h1>
	<p class="tagline">Symbols and tags for filtering your notes.</p>

	<img src="/docs/prismchart/thinkpad/ThinkPad-20260126-1.jpg" alt="ThinkPad Workspace" />

	<h2 id="symbols">Symbols</h2>
	<p class="section-intro">Everything in ThinkPad is organized by trading instrument.</p>

	<img src="/docs/prismchart/thinkpad/ThinkPad-20260126-2.jpg" alt="ThinkPad Symbol Manager" />

	<p>Two types of symbols exist. Database symbols are automatically detected from your trades.json file. User symbols, marked with a star, are manually added for instruments you plan to trade but haven't yet.</p>

	<p>To add a symbol, click the All button to open Symbol Manager, then click New Symbol. Enter the symbol name and click Apply.</p>

	<p>Filter your notes by checking or unchecking symbols in Symbol Manager. Only notes for selected symbols appear in the tree.</p>

	<p class="note">When you open ThinkPad, it auto-selects the current chart symbol if available.</p>

	<h2 id="tags">Tags</h2>
	<p class="section-intro">Categorize notes by strategy, outcome, or any system you prefer.</p>

	<img src="/docs/prismchart/thinkpad/ThinkPad-20260126-3.jpg" alt="ThinkPad Tag Manager" />

	<p>Click the All Tags button to open Tag Manager, then click New Tag. Enter a name like "breakout", "reversal", or "mistake" and click Apply.</p>

	<p>Tags in use display a count showing how many notes reference them. Empty tags show no count.</p>

	<p>Filter by selecting one or more tags in Tag Manager and clicking Apply. Only notes with those tags appear.</p>

	<p class="note">Tag strategy examples: setup types (breakout, reversal, trend), quality grades (A-setup, B-setup, mistake), or phases (planning, active, review).</p>
</DocsLayout>
